    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "To the Editor, We read with interest the recent article by Repici et al 1 in which the authors discuss the challenges of endoscopy in times of COVID-19 pandemic and suggest measures to minimize the risk of transmission in endoscopy units. We would appreciate to have authors' insight on some the aspects that will be discussed below.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "COVID-19 Pandemic: the long and difficult way back to work"
        },
        {
            "text": "Since the coronavirus infection (sars-cov-2) has become a worldwide health problem, many society guidelines have been published, dealing with contamination risks and prevention of infection during endoscopic procedures, including the correct use and removal of personal protective equipment (PPE). It is now recognized that endoscopic procedures in COVID-19 patients are highly infecting to all involved health care personnel. 1, 2 From the peak of the pandemic to the moment when most people get immunity against SARS-COV-2 (either by infection or by an effective vaccine), endoscopy units will have to resume their daily activities around the globe. It will be challenging to repeat the huge numbers of routine endoscopic procedures performed before the COVID-19 pandemic, considering the time spent for the correct use and removal of PPE, the shortage of rooms equipped with negative pressure ventilation, just to mention a few limitations. In this sense, we would like to have the authors' insights on the strategies that they will adopt facing this moment of transition. In addition to the measures to triage supect-for-COVID-19-infection patients before endoscopic procedures, would it be advisable to perform immunologic tests in health care personnel who did not develop (at least symptomatic) COVID-19? In theory, health care personnel who test negative both for serum IgM antibody and SARS-COV-2 polymerase-chainreaction (PCR) from nasal and oral swab, and test positive for serum IgG antibody against the virus, are immune to the SARS-COV-2 infection. [3] [4] [5] [6] [7] [8] One possible strategy would be to perform antibodies tests (IgM and IgG) first, followed by PCR in those positive for IgG. Based on the results, it would be easier to organize the endoscopy unit personnel working scales, assigning the susceptible workers to sectors where contact with patients is less intense. If possible and available, performing PCR in patients who will undergo endoscopic procedures could also help to define the proper management and better organize the endoscopy unit routine. 9 ",
